STEP 1 — Install Required Packages

Open terminal and run:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install git wget flex bison gperf python3 python3-pip python3-setuptools cmake ninja-build ccache libffi-dev libssl-dev dfu-util



STEP 2 — Create ESP32 Workspace

Run these commands one by one.

mkdir -p ~/esp32_projects
cd ~/esp32_projects

Check location:

pwd



STEP 3 — Clone ESP-IDF

Run this command:

git clone https://github.com/espressif/esp-idf.git

Wait until cloning completes.

You will see something like:

Cloning into 'esp-idf'...
Receiving objects...
Resolving deltas...



STEP 4 — Go inside ESP-IDF folder

Run:

cd ~/esp32_projects/esp-idf

Verify files:

ls

You should see files like:

CMakeLists.txt
components
docs
examples
install.sh
export.sh
tools



STEP 5 — Install ESP-IDF Toolchain

Run this command:

./install.sh

This script will automatically install:

ESP32 Xtensa compiler

Python packages

Flash tools

Build tools required for ESP32 development

⏱ Expected time: 10–20 minutes

During installation you will see messages like:

Installing ESP-IDF tools
Installing Python environment
Downloading xtensa-esp32 toolchain

Let it complete fully.



STEP 6 — Activate the Environment

After installation finishes, run:

source export.sh

You should see something like:

Setting IDF_PATH to /home/seetha/esp32_projects/esp-idf
Adding ESP-IDF tools to PATH



STEP 7 — Verify Installation

Run:

idf.py --version

Example output:

ESP-IDF v5.x

If you see this, the framework is ready.



STEP 8 — Make Environment Permanent

So you don't need to run export.sh every time:

echo 'source ~/esp32_projects/esp-idf/export.sh' >> ~/.bashrc

Reload:

source ~/.bashrc



STEP 9 — Go to Workspace

Run:

cd ~/esp32_projects

Verify:

pwd



STEP 10 — Create Project Folder

mkdir ble_tracking
cd ble_tracking

Check:

pwd



STEP 11 — Create Device Folders

Run:

mkdir beacon1 beacon2 scanner

Check:

ls

You should see:

beacon1
beacon2
scanner


